{"award_age":39.0,"bio_image":"full\/521abdb891c1759b81fda4fba0c01f692bf8af10.jpg","category":"Physiology or Medicine","country":"United States","date_of_birth":"1915-06-15T00:00:00.000Z","date_of_death":"2008-08-23T00:00:00.000Z","gender":"male","image_urls":["http:\/\/upload.wikimedia.org\/wikipedia\/en\/thumb\/c\/cb\/Thomas_Huckle_Weller.jpg\/200px-Thomas_Huckle_Weller.jpg"],"link":"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Thomas_H._Weller","mini_bio":"<p><b>Thomas Huckle Weller<\/b> (June 15, 1915 \u2013 August 23, 2008) was an American <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Virologist\" title=\"Virologist\" class=\"mw-redirect\">virologist<\/a>. He, <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/John_Franklin_Enders\" title=\"John Franklin Enders\">John Franklin Enders<\/a> and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Frederick_Chapman_Robbins\" title=\"Frederick Chapman Robbins\">Frederick Chapman Robbins<\/a> were awarded a <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nobel_Prize_in_Physiology_or_Medicine\" title=\"Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine\">Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine<\/a> in 1954 for showing how to cultivate <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Polio\" title=\"Polio\" class=\"mw-redirect\">poliomyelitis<\/a> viruses in a test tube, using a combination of human embryonic skin and muscle tissue.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Thomas_H._Weller#cite_note-1\"><span>[<\/span>1<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><\/p><p>Weller was born and grew up in <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Ann_Arbor\" title=\"Ann Arbor\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Ann Arbor<\/a>, <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Michigan\" title=\"Michigan\">Michigan<\/a>, and then went to the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/University_of_Michigan\" title=\"University of Michigan\">University of Michigan<\/a>, where his father <a href=\"\/w\/index.php?title=Carl_Vernon_Weller&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" class=\"new\" title=\"Carl Vernon Weller (page does not exist)\">Carl Vernon Weller<\/a> was a professor in the Department of Pathology. At Michigan, he studied medical zoology and received a B.S. and an M.S., with his masters thesis on fish parasites. In 1936, Weller entered <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Harvard_Medical_School\" title=\"Harvard Medical School\">Harvard Medical School<\/a>, and in 1939 began working under John Franklin Enders, with whom he would later (along with Frederick Chapman Robbins) share the Nobel Prize. It was Enders who got Weller involved in researching viruses and tissue-culture techniques for determining infectious disease causes. Weller received his MD in 1940, and went to work at Children's Hospital in <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Boston\" title=\"Boston\">Boston<\/a>. In 1942, during World War II, he entered the Army Medical Corps and was stationed at the <a href=\"\/w\/index.php?title=Antilles_Medical_Laboratory&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" class=\"new\" title=\"Antilles Medical Laboratory (page does not exist)\">Antilles Medical Laboratory<\/a> in <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Puerto_Rico\" title=\"Puerto Rico\">Puerto Rico<\/a>, earning the rank of Major and heading the facility's Departments of Bacteriology, Virology and Parasitology. After the War, he returned to Children's Hospital in Boston, and it was there in 1947, that he rejoined Enders in the newly created Research Division of Infectious Diseases. After several leading positions, in July 1954, he was appointed Tropical Public Health Department Head at the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Harvard_School_of_Public_Health\" title=\"Harvard School of Public Health\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Harvard School of Public Health<\/a>. Weller also served from 1953 to 1959 as Director of the Commission on Parasitic Diseases of the American <a href=\"\/w\/index.php?title=Armed_Forces_Epidemiological_Board&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" class=\"new\" title=\"Armed Forces Epidemiological Board (page does not exist)\">Armed Forces Epidemiological Board<\/a>. In 1954 he was awarded the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/George_Ledlie\" title=\"George Ledlie\" class=\"mw-redirect\">George Ledlie<\/a> prize in recognition of his research on <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Rubella\" title=\"Rubella\">rubella<\/a>, <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Polio\" title=\"Polio\" class=\"mw-redirect\">polio<\/a> and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Cytomegalovirus\" title=\"Cytomegalovirus\">cytomegalovirus<\/a>(CMV) viruses.<\/p><p>In addition to his research on <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Polio\" title=\"Polio\" class=\"mw-redirect\">polio<\/a>, for which he won the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nobel_Prize\" title=\"Nobel Prize\">Nobel Prize<\/a>, Weller also contributed to treating <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Schistosomiasis\" title=\"Schistosomiasis\">schistosomiasis<\/a>, and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Coxsackie_A_virus\" title=\"Coxsackie A virus\">Coxsackie viruses<\/a>. He was also the first to isolate the virus responsible for <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Varicella\" title=\"Varicella\" class=\"mw-redirect\">varicella<\/a>.<\/p><p>In 1945, Weller married Kathleen Fahey. They had two sons and two daughters.<\/p>","name":"Thomas H. Weller","place_of_birth":"Ann Arbor ,  Michigan","place_of_death":"Needham ,  Massachusetts","text":"Thomas H. Weller , Physiology or Medicine, 1954","year":1954.0}